Do you want to own one of the @sportful jerseys or @iamspecialized helmets I actually wore at the Tour de France and, at the same time, contribute to a worthy cause? Here's your chance! 

Click on the link in my bio and place your bid in the auction for my original, signed jersey or helmet. All proceeds will go to @outride in order to support the incredible work they do with children, through bicycles! 

Link -> In Bio

What is @outride 
Outride is a non-profit cycling organization based in the U.S. that works with schools, community partners, coaches, teams, and cyclists to promote a more equitable, inclusive, and healthy future for youth. Their mission is to make cycling more accessible to young people so that every child can experience the freedom, joy, and community that cycling can provide.

What does @outride do? 
Conduct and fund research to better understand how bicycling affects our brains, how we think and feel. We work with schools to help students achieve academic, health, and social success. Outride provides middle schools with everything they need to get their 6th-8th grade students biking: Bikes, helmets, curriculum, and teacher training. Through the Outride Fund, access to bicycling increases at the community level by awarding matching grants to programs that get more kids on bikes.

Hello everybody!

I'd like to give you an update on my condition after my withdrawal from the @letourdefrance last Thursday.

First of all, I'd like to thank the @borahansgrohe management, the team's doctors, and in particular our Head Doctor, Christopher Edler, for their support and guidance since my crash on stage 3. Secondly, I'm so grateful for all the get-well messages that I received from my teammates, friends, and fans from all over the world. They are greatly appreciated.

On stage 3, the chainring hit my knee and entered the skin above the patella, leaving a deep wound. We cleaned the wound as much as possible to prevent infection because of the dirt from the chain oil. However, after a few days, an inflammation developed in the bursa on top of the patella, and, unfortunately, antibiotic treatment couldn’t prevent an infection. The only option was to stop racing at the Tour de France and get the bursa surgically removed. Luckily it was only a superficial infection and the knee joint is not involved in this at all. Also, I'd like to thank the doctors and medical staff at IM2S clinic in Monaco for performing an excellent surgery on such short notice and for their great cooperation with the team's medical staff.

I'm feeling well right now and in a couple of days, I'll be able to train again on my rollers. If all goes well, I'll be riding my bike on the road very soon.

Thank you!!!

Congratulations to the winners, @alsamen from the United Arab Emirates,  @mwashanedy from Kenya and @sprint.king.blink from the Turks and Caicos Islands! You will be contacted to receive your prize.

I will pick three entries at random and the winners will be announced a week from now, during the second rest day.
